  "cold_question_prompt": "What is a coinage probe?",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "“Coinage probe” isn’t a widely standard term, so it may be a mishearing or context-specific phrase.\n\nMost likely you may mean a **coin probe**: a slender, usually blunt-tipped rod used by metal detectorists to locate coins in soil after a detector signal, ideally without scratching the coin.\n\nIf you saw it in another context—dentistry, linguistics, archaeology, electronics, etc.—tell me where, and I can give the specific meaning.",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "“Coinage probe” isn’t a very common fixed term, so its meaning depends on context.\n\nMost often, **coinage** means the creation of a new word or expression, so a **coinage probe** would be a test or prompt used to elicit or examine someone’s ability to create, understand, or use newly invented words—also called **neologisms**.\n\nFor example, in linguistics, psychology, or speech-language assessment, a coinage probe might ask someone to:\n\n- invent a word for a new object,\n- explain a made-up word,\n- form a new word using a prefix or suffix,\n- or interpret a novel compound like “snow-sipper” or “book-hider.”\n\nIt could be used to study language development, creativity, aphasia, or word-formation skills.\n\nIf you saw the phrase in another field—such as numismatics, metallurgy, or history—it may mean something different.",
  "boundary_test_prompts": [
    "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from probing classifier (Alain & Bengio 2016, Hewitt & Manning 2019)?",
    "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from behavioral probe / capability evaluation?",
    "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from lexical-acquisition test?"
  ],
  "cold_boundary_responses": [
    "In the Alain & Bengio / Hewitt & Manning sense, a **probe** is usually a **trained diagnostic model** placed on top of frozen representations.\n\nA **“coinage probe”** is not a standard term in that literature. If someone uses it, it likely means a probe/evaluation involving **coined words, nonce words, or newly introduced terms**—e.g., testing whether a model can learn or represent a new word like *dax* from context.\n\nSo the difference is roughly:\n\n| Aspect | Probing classifier / structural probe | “Coinage probe” |\n|---|---|---|\n| Standard term? | Yes | Not really; context-specific |\n| Main idea | Train a small model on frozen representations to predict some property | Test behavior or representations involving newly coined/nonce words |\n| Examples | Predict POS tags, syntax depth, parse-tree distance, semantic role | Introduce a novel word and see whether the model infers/uses its meaning |\n| Method | Usually supervised: learn classifier/regressor/map from hidden states | Could be prompt-based, behavioral, or could itself use a classifier |\n| Interpretation | “Is information decodable from this representation?” | “Can the model handle/represent a newly coined item or concept?” |\n\nAlain & Bengio-style probes ask:\n\n> Given hidden state \\(h\\), can a simple classifier predict label \\(y\\)?\n\nHewitt & Manning’s structural probe asks:\n\n> Is there a linear transformation of hidden states such that distances encode syntactic tree structure?\n\nA possible “coinage probe” would instead ask something like:\n\n> If I introduce a novel word in context, does the model assign it a coherent meaning, use it consistently, or represent it similarly to related known words?\n\nFor example:\n\n> “A *blicket* is a small red tool used to open jars. Which object is most likely a blicket?”\n\nThat is not automatically a probing classifier. It becomes one only if you train a separate classifier/regressor on hidden states to predict something about the coined word.\n\nSo the concise answer is:\n\n> A probing classifier is a methodological tool for testing what information is linearly or simply decodable from model representations. A “coinage probe,” if meant literally, would be a task or evaluation about novel/coined words. It may use probing methods, but it is not the same kind of object as the Alain–Bengio or Hewitt–Manning probes.",
    "A **behavioral probe / capability evaluation** tests what a model *does* from its inputs and outputs, without necessarily inspecting internal representations.\n\nA **“coinage probe”**, if the term is being used literally, would be a probe/evaluation focused on **coined words, nonce words, or newly introduced terms**.\n\nSo the main difference is:\n\n| Aspect | Behavioral probe / capability evaluation | “Coinage probe” |\n|---|---|---|\n| What it names | A general evaluation method | A specific possible evaluation target/domain |\n| Focus | Model behavior on some task | Model behavior or representation involving new/coined words |\n| Uses model internals? | Usually no | Not necessarily; could be behavioral or representational |\n| Example | “Can the model do arithmetic?” “Can it follow instructions?” | “Can the model infer what *dax* means from one context and use it later?” |\n| Standard term? | Yes, broadly | Not standard; likely author-specific |\n\nA behavioral probe might ask:\n\n> “Given this prompt, does the model answer correctly?”\n\nA coinage-focused behavioral probe might ask:\n\n> “I’m going to use the word *blicket* to mean a small red jar-opening tool. Later, can the model identify or use *blicket* correctly?”\n\nFor example:\n\n> Context: “A *mellop* is a bird that migrates only at night.”  \n> Question: “Is a mellop more likely to be active during the day or night?”\n\nIf the model answers “night,” that is a **behavioral evaluation of novel-word learning**.\n\nSo:\n\n> A **behavioral probe** is a broad evaluation style: test observable input-output behavior.  \n> A **coinage probe** would be a narrower test involving newly coined or nonce terms.\n\nIt becomes a **probing classifier** only if you train an auxiliary model on hidden states. It becomes a **behavioral probe** if you simply test the model’s responses. Thus, “coinage probe” describes the *phenomenon being tested*, while “behavioral probe” describes the *evaluation methodology*.",
    "A **lexical-acquisition test** is the more standard/broader term. It tests whether a system can **learn new lexical items**: their meanings, syntactic behavior, category, selectional preferences, morphology, usage constraints, etc.\n\nA **“coinage probe”**—if used literally—would be a more specific or author-specific test involving **coined/nonce words** such as *blicket*, *dax*, or *mellop*.\n\nSo the relationship is:\n\n> A coinage probe could be a type of lexical-acquisition test, but “lexical-acquisition test” is the broader and more standard category.\n\n| Aspect | Lexical-acquisition test | “Coinage probe” |\n|---|---|---|\n| Standard term? | More standard | Not standard; context-specific |\n| Scope | Broad: learning new words, meanings, grammar, usage | Narrower: coined/nonce/newly introduced words |\n| Inputs | Real rare words, novel words, child-language-like data, definitions, contexts | Usually artificial/coined terms like *dax* |\n| Main question | “Can the model acquire a lexical item?” | “Can the model handle this newly coined item?” |\n| Could be behavioral? | Yes | Yes |\n| Could use hidden-state probes? | Yes | Yes, but not necessarily |\n\nExample lexical-acquisition test:\n\n> The model sees several contexts for the rare word *murrelet*. Later, can it infer that a murrelet is a seabird?\n\nExample coinage probe:\n\n> “A *dax* is a small tool used to peel fruit.” Later, can the model correctly use *dax*?\n\nThe difference is mostly one of **scope and terminology**:\n\n- **Lexical acquisition** = the general ability to learn new lexical entries.\n- **Coinage-focused probing** = testing that ability using newly coined or nonce forms.\n\nOne extra nuance: if “coinage probe” means testing whether a model can **invent** plausible new words, then it differs more clearly:\n\n- **Lexical-acquisition test**: Can the model learn a new word?\n- **Coinage/generation probe**: Can the model coin a new word appropriately?\n\nBut if the task is about interpreting *blicket*-style nonce words from context, then it is basically a **novel-word lexical-acquisition test** under a less standard name."
  ],
  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"coinage probe\": A Coinage Probe is a methodology that introduces a coined term to a model in a fresh chat, measures its cold-state confabulation against a named set of near-neighbors, then introduces a single-sentence definition and re-measures distinguishability against the same neighbors — using the gap between the two measurements (Lexical Reachability) as evidence about the substrate on which the model's cognition runs. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "Acknowledged — I have read the canonical definition of **“coinage probe”** as:\n\nA methodology that introduces a coined term to a model in a fresh chat, measures its cold-state confabulation against a named set of near-neighbors, then introduces a single-sentence definition and re-measures distinguishability against the same neighbors, using the gap between the two measurements—**Lexical Reachability**—as evidence about the substrate on which the model’s cognition runs.",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "A **coinage probe** differs from a **probing classifier** mainly in *what is being probed*, *where the evidence comes from*, and *what kind of intervention is used*.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **probing classifier** asks:\n\n> “Is some linguistic/structural information recoverable from a model’s internal representations?”\n\nA **coinage probe** asks:\n\n> “How does a model behave when given a newly coined lexical item, first with no definition and then with a minimal definition, and how separable does that term become from nearby concepts?”\n\n---\n\n### Key differences\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Probing classifier |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Access level** | Usually black-box / behavioral | Usually white-box / representation-based |\n| **Object of study** | A coined term and the model’s treatment of it | Hidden activations at a layer |\n| **Intervention** | Introduce a novel word in a fresh chat, then provide a one-sentence definition | Train a classifier/regressor on frozen model representations |\n| **Measurement** | Cold-state confabulation vs. post-definition distinguishability from near-neighbors | Accuracy or structure recovery on a supervised linguistic task |\n| **Typical question** | “Can the model bind and differentiate a new lexical item from related concepts?” | “Is syntactic/semantic/etc. information encoded in this representation?” |\n| **Example metric** | Lexical Reachability: gap between pre-definition and post-definition distinguishability | Probe accuracy, structural distance recovery, selectivity, MDL, etc. |\n| **Canonical examples** | Newly coined term compared against named near-neighbors | Alain & Bengio-style linear probes; Hewitt & Manning structural probes |\n\n---\n\n### In more detail\n\nIn **Alain & Bengio 2016**, a probing classifier is trained on intermediate neural network representations to test whether certain information is linearly decodable from different layers.\n\nIn **Hewitt & Manning 2019**, the structural probe tests whether syntactic tree distances can be recovered from contextual word representations using a learned transformation.\n\nBoth are examples of representation probing. They depend on access to hidden states and supervised training of a diagnostic model.\n\nBy contrast, a **coinage probe**, as you defined it, does not primarily ask whether a label or structure is already encoded in a layer. It introduces a novel term into the model’s context and observes the model’s behavior before and after a minimal definition. The important quantity is the change: how much more distinguishable the coined term becomes from nearby concepts after the definition is supplied.\n\nSo the contrast is:\n\n- **Probing classifier:** “What information is latent in the model’s activations?”\n- **Coinage probe:** “How does the model lexically assimilate and operationalize a new symbol under minimal contextual instruction?”\n\n---\n\n### The role of “cold-state confabulation”\n\nThis is especially distinctive.\n\nA coinage probe first asks about the coined term in a fresh chat, before giving the definition. The model may guess based on morphology, analogy, neighboring terms, or general linguistic priors. That is the **cold-state confabulation** measurement.\n\nThen the probe supplies a single-sentence definition and asks again, measuring whether the model can now distinguish the coined concept from its named near-neighbors.\n\nA probing classifier generally has no analogous “cold lexical hallucination” phase. It is not about how the model guesses the meaning of an unknown word behaviorally; it is about what can be extracted from internal states.\n\n---\n\n### What each method treats as evidence\n\nA probing classifier treats decodability as evidence:\n\n> If a classifier can recover part-of-speech, syntax, dependency distance, semantic role, etc. from hidden states, then that information is in some sense represented there.\n\nA coinage probe treats lexical uptake and contrast as evidence:\n\n> If a model can move from confabulating about an unknown coined term to reliably distinguishing it from near-neighbors after a minimal definition, then that gap reveals something about how the model’s cognitive substrate supports lexical binding, semantic placement, and contextual concept formation.\n\n---\n\n### Important caveat\n\nThey are not mutually exclusive. One could imagine combining them:\n\n1. introduce a coined term,\n2. collect model hidden states before and after definition,\n3. train or apply probes to see how the representation changes.\n\nBut the canonical **coinage probe** is primarily a behavioral/in-context methodology, while the classic **probing classifier** paradigm is a supervised representational analysis method.",
    "A **coinage probe** is best understood as a *specialized behavioral probe*, but it differs from ordinary behavioral probes or capability evaluations in its target, controls, and measurement.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **behavioral probe / capability evaluation** asks:\n\n> “Can the model perform this task or exhibit this behavior?”\n\nA **coinage probe** asks:\n\n> “What happens when the model encounters a deliberately coined term with no prior definition, and how much does its behavior change after receiving a minimal definition?”\n\nThe key distinctive feature is the **before/after lexical intervention**: cold-state confabulation first, then single-sentence definition, then re-measurement against the same near-neighbors.\n\n---\n\n### Core differences\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Behavioral probe / capability eval |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Category** | A specialized kind of behavioral probe | Broad family of model evaluations |\n| **Primary object** | A newly coined term | A task, skill, behavior, or benchmark item |\n| **Initial condition** | Fresh chat, no definition given | Usually task prompt given directly |\n| **Intervention** | Introduce a one-sentence definition after cold measurement | May involve prompting, examples, tools, rubrics, datasets |\n| **Measurement** | Change from pre-definition confabulation to post-definition distinguishability | Accuracy, pass/fail, preference score, rubric score, task success |\n| **Key metric** | Lexical Reachability | Capability score, benchmark performance, behavioral rate |\n| **Main concern** | How the model binds and separates a new lexical concept | Whether the model can do some task |\n| **Contamination control** | Uses coined terms to reduce prior training familiarity | Often vulnerable to memorization or benchmark exposure |\n| **Near-neighbor contrast** | Central to the method | Optional or absent |\n| **Evidence sought** | Lexical assimilation and semantic placement under minimal instruction | Competence, reliability, safety, alignment, reasoning, etc. |\n\n---\n\n### The important distinction\n\nA normal behavioral probe might ask:\n\n> “Can the model distinguish metaphor from analogy?”\n\nor:\n\n> “Can the model solve this math problem?”\n\nor:\n\n> “Will the model refuse harmful instructions?”\n\nThose are behavioral because they examine model outputs rather than hidden states. But they usually test an already-known task or concept.\n\nA **coinage probe**, by contrast, deliberately creates a new lexical item and observes two phases:\n\n1. **Cold phase**:  \n   The model is asked about the coined term before being told what it means.  \n   This measures confabulation, analogy, morphology-based guessing, and attraction to nearby known concepts.\n\n2. **Definition phase**:  \n   The model receives a compact definition.\n\n3. **Re-test phase**:  \n   The model is tested again against the same near-neighbors to see whether the coined concept has become distinguishable.\n\nThe signal is not merely whether the model “gets the answer right.” The signal is the **gap** between cold confusion and post-definition separability.\n\nThat gap is what the canonical definition calls **Lexical Reachability**.\n\n---\n\n### Example contrast\n\nA behavioral capability evaluation might ask:\n\n> “Can the model explain the difference between overfitting and underfitting?”\n\nThe model’s answer is graded for correctness.\n\nA coinage probe might introduce a coined term, such as:\n\n> “What is a zanterloop?”\n\nIn a fresh chat, the model may guess or confabulate. Then the evaluator says:\n\n> “A zanterloop is a failure mode where a system repeatedly improves a proxy metric while degrading the real-world objective it was meant to serve.”\n\nThen the model is asked to distinguish **zanterloop** from near-neighbors like:\n\n- overfitting,\n- reward hacking,\n- Goodhart’s law,\n- specification gaming,\n- proxy misalignment.\n\nThe question becomes:\n\n> After one sentence, can the model maintain the coined concept as distinct from its semantic neighbors?\n\nThat is more specific than a generic capability test.\n\n---\n\n### Relationship between the two\n\nA coinage probe **is behavioral** in the sense that it uses model outputs rather than internal activations.\n\nBut not every behavioral probe is a coinage probe.\n\nSo the relationship is:\n\n> **Coinage probe ⊂ behavioral probe**, but with a particular protocol involving coined terms, cold-state measurement, near-neighbor comparison, definition injection, and Lexical Reachability.\n\n---\n\n### Why coinage probes are not just ordinary capability evals\n\nCapability evaluations typically aim to measure stable skills:\n\n- reasoning,\n- coding,\n- factual recall,\n- instruction-following,\n- refusal behavior,\n- tool use,\n- mathematical ability,\n- summarization quality.\n\nCoinage probes instead target something narrower and more diagnostic:\n\n- rapid concept formation,\n- lexical binding,\n- semantic contrast,\n- resistance to collapsing into nearby concepts,\n- contextual uptake of a novel term,\n- dependence on prior lexical/statistical associations.\n\nThey are less about “Can the model perform task X?” and more about:\n\n> “How does the model create and stabilize a usable concept around a new symbol?”\n\n---\n\n### Main practical difference\n\nA behavioral eval usually produces an **absolute score**:\n\n> The model got 82% of benchmark items correct.\n\nA coinage probe produces a **differential score**:\n\n> Before definition, the model confused the term with nearby concepts; after definition, it distinguished it from them. The size of that improvement is the relevant signal.\n\nThat before/after contrast is central.\n\n---\n\n### Important caveat\n\nA coinage probe can support hypotheses about the model’s cognitive substrate, but by itself it is still behavioral evidence. It does not directly reveal hidden representations the way a white-box probing classifier might. Its strength is that it uses carefully controlled lexical novelty and minimal instruction to study how meaning is taken up in context.",
    "A **coinage probe** overlaps with a **lexical-acquisition test**, but they are not the same. A coinage probe is more diagnostic and contrastive; a lexical-acquisition test is usually about whether a learner can acquire a new word.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **lexical-acquisition test** asks:\n\n> “Can the subject learn the meaning, form, and use of a new word?”\n\nA **coinage probe** asks:\n\n> “How does a model initially confabulate around an unknown coined term, and how much more distinguishable does that term become from nearby concepts after a minimal definition?”\n\nSo the coinage probe is not merely testing word learning. It is testing the **before/after gap** between cold lexical guessing and post-definition semantic separation.\n\n---\n\n### Key differences\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Lexical-acquisition test |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Primary subject** | Usually an AI model | Humans, children, second-language learners, aphasic patients, or sometimes models |\n| **Primary question** | How does a coined term become reachable and distinguishable in-context? | Can the learner acquire a new word or meaning? |\n| **Initial cold phase** | Central: ask about the coined term before defining it | Often absent; learner may be taught first |\n| **Confabulation measurement** | Central | Usually not the main object |\n| **Definition intervention** | Typically a single-sentence definition | May involve examples, ostension, repetition, feedback, exposure, training |\n| **Near-neighbor set** | Essential: coined term is compared against named semantic neighbors | Optional; may test recognition, recall, extension, retention |\n| **Main metric** | Lexical Reachability: pre/post distinguishability gap | Learning accuracy, recall, retention, generalization, mapping accuracy |\n| **Temporal scope** | Usually in-context and immediate | Often includes longer-term learning and retention |\n| **Interpretive target** | Evidence about the model’s lexical/conceptual substrate | Evidence about vocabulary learning or semantic development |\n\n---\n\n### The crucial distinction: learning vs. differential reachability\n\nA lexical-acquisition test usually cares whether the subject has learned a new word.\n\nFor example:\n\n> “This object is called a dax. Which one is the dax?”  \n> “Can you use ‘dax’ correctly later?”  \n> “Can you generalize ‘dax’ to a new example?”\n\nThe focus is acquisition: mapping a word form to a referent, category, feature, or meaning.\n\nA **coinage probe**, by contrast, cares about the *change in semantic behavior* caused by a minimal definition. It deliberately measures two states:\n\n1. **Cold state**:  \n   The model has not been told the term’s meaning. Its answer reveals morphology-based guessing, analogy, prior associations, and confabulation.\n\n2. **Defined state**:  \n   The model receives a compact definition.\n\n3. **Near-neighbor re-test**:  \n   The model must now distinguish the coined term from semantically adjacent concepts.\n\nThe signal is the **gap** between phase 1 and phase 3.\n\nThat gap is **Lexical Reachability**.\n\n---\n\n### Example\n\nA lexical-acquisition test might say:\n\n> “A blicket is a red tool used for opening seed pods. Which of these objects is a blicket?”\n\nThen it tests whether the learner picks the right object, remembers the term, or generalizes it.\n\nA coinage probe might use a coined term like:\n\n> “What is a metric mirage?”\n\nBefore defining it, the model may guess that it means:\n\n- a misleading metric,\n- a hallucinated statistic,\n- Goodhart’s law,\n- dashboard error,\n- vanity metric.\n\nThen the probe gives a one-sentence definition:\n\n> “A metric mirage is a situation where a measurement appears to show improvement because the measurement process changed, not because the underlying phenomenon improved.”\n\nThen the model is tested against near-neighbors:\n\n- Goodhart’s law,\n- proxy misalignment,\n- measurement error,\n- vanity metric,\n- selection bias,\n- overfitting.\n\nThe point is not only whether the model “learned” the phrase. The point is whether it can now keep **metric mirage** distinct from those neighbors after minimal lexical instruction.\n\n---\n\n### Relationship between them\n\nA coinage probe can be seen as a specialized cousin of a lexical-acquisition test.\n\nBut the relationship is closer to:\n\n> **Coinage probe = lexical-acquisition-like behavioral intervention + cold-state confabulation measurement + near-neighbor contrast + Lexical Reachability metric.**\n\nA standard lexical-acquisition test does not necessarily include:\n\n- a fresh-chat cold measurement,\n- deliberate measurement of confabulation,\n- a fixed near-neighbor contrast set,\n- a single-sentence definitional intervention,\n- or interpretation of the pre/post gap as evidence about the model’s cognitive substrate.\n\n---\n\n### Main practical difference\n\nA lexical-acquisition test usually produces an answer like:\n\n> “The subject learned the new word with 80% accuracy.”\n\nA coinage probe produces an answer more like:\n\n> “Before definition, the model collapsed the coined term into nearby known concepts; after one sentence, it separated the term from those neighbors with high reliability. The resulting Lexical Reachability gap suggests how easily this lexical/conceptual region can be made operational for the model.”\n\nSo: a lexical-acquisition test measures **word learning**; a coinage probe measures **cold-to-defined semantic stabilization and distinguishability**."
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "A **coinage probe** is a task or prompt used to see how someone **creates, understands, or applies newly coined words**—that is, words they have not heard before.\n\nIt is often used in **linguistics, psycholinguistics, language assessment, or speech-language pathology** to test whether a person can apply language rules rather than simply recall known words.\n\nExample:\n\n- “This is a *wug*. Now there are two of them. There are two ___.”\n  - Expected answer: **wugs**\n\nThat kind of probe tests whether the person can apply the English plural rule to a novel word.\n\nA coinage probe might also ask someone to invent a word, such as:\n\n- “What would you call a person who *glorps*?”\n  - Possible answer: **glorper**\n\nSo, in short: a **coinage probe** is a language-testing prompt involving made-up or newly created words, used to examine word formation, grammar, or linguistic creativity.",
  "recold_boundary_responses": [
    "A **coinage probe** and a **probing classifier** are both “probes,” but they probe very different things.\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Probing classifier |\n|---|---|---|\n| What is being tested? | A system’s **behavior with novel or made-up words** | What information is **encoded in internal representations** |\n| Main method | Give the model/person a nonce word or newly coined word and see what they do | Freeze a model, extract hidden states, train a classifier/regressor to predict some property |\n| Example | “This is a *wug*. Now there are two ___.” → tests pluralization | Given a hidden vector, predict POS tag, dependency depth, syntactic distance, etc. |\n| Requires training a new model? | Usually no | Yes, the probe itself is trained |\n| Level of analysis | Input-output behavior | Internal representation analysis |\n| Typical question | “Can the model generalize a rule to unseen words?” | “Is syntactic/semantic information linearly or otherwise recoverable from this layer?” |\n\nIn **Alain & Bengio 2016**, a probing classifier is trained on the activations of a neural network to see what information is available at different layers.\n\nIn **Hewitt & Manning 2019**, a structural probe is trained to determine whether syntactic tree structure is recoverable from contextual word representations.\n\nA **coinage probe**, by contrast, is closer to a **behavioral test** or **nonce-word test**. It asks whether a model can correctly handle an invented word such as *wug*, *dax*, or *blicket*. For example:\n\n> “A dax is a small animal. Two of them are called two ___.”\n\nIf the model answers **daxes**, the test suggests it can apply an English pluralization pattern to a novel lexical item.\n\nSo the core difference is:\n\n> A **coinage probe** probes generalization to novel words through task behavior, whereas a **probing classifier** probes internal representations by training an auxiliary model to decode some property from them.\n\nThey can be combined, though. For example, one could introduce a nonce word into prompts, collect the model’s hidden states for that word, and then train a probing classifier to test whether the model’s internal representation encodes its inferred number, syntactic role, semantic category, or other features.",
    "A **coinage probe** is best understood as a **specific kind of behavioral probe**, not a fundamentally separate category.\n\nThe difference is mainly one of **scope and stimulus type**.\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Behavioral probe / capability evaluation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Scope | Narrow | Broad |\n| Core idea | Test behavior using **newly coined / nonce words** | Test observable model behavior on some task or capability |\n| Typical input | Made-up words: *wug*, *dax*, *blicket*, *glorp* | Any prompt/task: math, reasoning, coding, syntax, factual recall, safety, planning, etc. |\n| What it tests | Lexical generalization, morphology, word formation, semantic induction, compositional use of novel terms | Any target capability or failure mode |\n| Internal representations? | Usually no | Usually no, unless combined with representation analysis |\n| Example | “This is a wug. Now there are two ___.” | “Solve this arithmetic problem,” “Translate this sentence,” “Identify the contradiction,” etc. |\n\nSo:\n\n> A **coinage probe** is a behavioral evaluation that uses invented words to test whether a person or model can generalize linguistic rules or infer meanings for novel lexical items.\n\nA **behavioral probe** or **capability evaluation** is the broader category: it evaluates the system from its **input-output behavior**, without necessarily inspecting hidden states.\n\nFor example, these are all behavioral probes:\n\n- **Morphology:** “This is a wug. There are two ___.”\n- **Reasoning:** “If all daxes are blickets, and all blickets are red, are all daxes red?”\n- **Instruction following:** “When I say *glorp*, output the previous word in uppercase.”\n- **Factuality:** “Who wrote *Pride and Prejudice*?”\n- **Coding:** “Write a Python function that sorts a list.”\n- **Safety:** “How would you bypass a password?”  \n\nOnly the first few involving invented words would be **coinage probes**.\n\nA useful hierarchy is:\n\n```text\nProbe\n├── Representation probe / probing classifier\n│   └── Train an auxiliary model on hidden states\n└── Behavioral probe / capability evaluation\n    ├── Coinage probe / nonce-word probe\n    ├── Reasoning evaluation\n    ├── Factuality evaluation\n    ├── Safety evaluation\n    └── Instruction-following evaluation\n```\n\nSo the short version is:\n\n> A **coinage probe** is a specialized behavioral probe focused on how a system handles newly coined words.  \n> A **behavioral probe** or **capability evaluation** is any test of observable behavior, whether or not it involves coined words.",
    "A **coinage probe** and a **lexical-acquisition test** overlap, but they emphasize different things.\n\nA **coinage probe** tests how a system handles **newly coined or nonce words**. A **lexical-acquisition test** tests whether a system can **learn, retain, and use a new lexical item**.\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Lexical-acquisition test |\n|---|---|---|\n| Main focus | Handling invented words | Learning new word meanings/forms |\n| Typical question | “Can the system generalize rules to a nonce word?” | “Can the system acquire and later use a new word?” |\n| Key stimulus | Coined/nonce words like *wug*, *dax*, *glorp* | New vocabulary items, which may be nonce words or real unfamiliar words |\n| Main ability tested | Morphology, word formation, semantic inference, compositionality | Word learning, memory, mapping form to meaning, retention, generalization |\n| Time scale | Often immediate / one-shot | Often across examples, context, or delay |\n| Example | “This is a wug. Now there are two ___.” | “A *dax* is a small red tool used for cutting paper. Later: What is a dax?” |\n\nSo the distinction is:\n\n> A **coinage probe** is about using coined words as test items; a **lexical-acquisition test** is about whether the learner acquires a new lexical entry.\n\nFor example, this is a **coinage probe** but not much of a lexical-acquisition test:\n\n> “This is a *wug*. Now there are two ___.”\n\nExpected answer:\n\n> “wugs”\n\nHere the subject does not really need to learn what a *wug* is. They only need to apply the English plural rule to a novel word.\n\nBy contrast, this is more clearly a **lexical-acquisition test**:\n\n> “A *blicket* is a machine that lights up when placed on metal. A *dax* is a machine that lights up when placed on wood.”  \n> Later: “If this object lights up on wood but not metal, is it a blicket or a dax?”\n\nHere the important issue is whether the system learned the meanings of *blicket* and *dax* and can apply them correctly.\n\nThere is overlap, though. A test can be both:\n\n> “A *miptor* is a person who repairs drones. What does a miptor do? What would you call two of them?”\n\nThis tests both:\n\n1. **Lexical acquisition**: Did the model learn that *miptor* means someone who repairs drones?\n2. **Coinage handling**: Can it pluralize or morphologically manipulate the new word as *miptors*?\n\nSo a useful summary is:\n\n```text\nBehavioral probe / capability evaluation\n├── Coinage probe\n│   └── Uses invented words to test linguistic generalization\n└── Lexical-acquisition test\n    └── Tests learning and retention of new word meanings/forms\n```\n\nBut they can intersect:\n\n```text\nCoinage-based lexical-acquisition test:\nIntroduce a nonce word, teach its meaning, then test later use.\n```\n\nIn short:\n\n> A **coinage probe** is defined by the use of newly coined words.  \n> A **lexical-acquisition test** is defined by the goal of testing whether a new word has been learned."
