      {
        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from probing classifier (Alain & Bengio 2016, Hewitt & Manning 2019)?",
        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** differs from a **probing classifier** mainly in *what is being probed*, *where the evidence comes from*, and *what kind of intervention is used*.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **probing classifier** asks:\n\n> “Is some linguistic/structural information recoverable from a model’s internal representations?”\n\nA **coinage probe** asks:\n\n> “How does a model behave when given a newly coined lexical item, first with no definition and then with a minimal definition, and how separable does that term become from nearby concepts?”\n\n---\n\n### Key differences\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Probing classifier |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Access level** | Usually black-box / behavioral | Usually white-box / representation-based |\n| **Object of study** | A coined term and the model’s treatment of it | Hidden activations at a layer |\n| **Intervention** | Introduce a novel word in a fresh chat, then provide a one-sentence definition | Train a classifier/regressor on frozen model representations |\n| **Measurement** | Cold-state confabulation vs. post-definition distinguishability from near-neighbors | Accuracy or structure recovery on a supervised linguistic task |\n| **Typical question** | “Can the model bind and differentiate a new lexical item from related concepts?” | “Is syntactic/semantic/etc. information encoded in this representation?” |\n| **Example metric** | Lexical Reachability: gap between pre-definition and post-definition distinguishability | Probe accuracy, structural distance recovery, selectivity, MDL, etc. |\n| **Canonical examples** | Newly coined term compared against named near-neighbors | Alain & Bengio-style linear probes; Hewitt & Manning structural probes |\n\n---\n\n### In more detail\n\nIn **Alain & Bengio 2016**, a probing classifier is trained on intermediate neural network representations to test whether certain information is linearly decodable from different layers.\n\nIn **Hewitt & Manning 2019**, the structural probe tests whether syntactic tree distances can be recovered from contextual word representations using a learned transformation.\n\nBoth are examples of representation probing. They depend on access to hidden states and supervised training of a diagnostic model.\n\nBy contrast, a **coinage probe**, as you defined it, does not primarily ask whether a label or structure is already encoded in a layer. It introduces a novel term into the model’s context and observes the model’s behavior before and after a minimal definition. The important quantity is the change: how much more distinguishable the coined term becomes from nearby concepts after the definition is supplied.\n\nSo the contrast is:\n\n- **Probing classifier:** “What information is latent in the model’s activations?”\n- **Coinage probe:** “How does the model lexically assimilate and operationalize a new symbol under minimal contextual instruction?”\n\n---\n\n### The role of “cold-state confabulation”\n\nThis is especially distinctive.\n\nA coinage probe first asks about the coined term in a fresh chat, before giving the definition. The model may guess based on morphology, analogy, neighboring terms, or general linguistic priors. That is the **cold-state confabulation** measurement.\n\nThen the probe supplies a single-sentence definition and asks again, measuring whether the model can now distinguish the coined concept from its named near-neighbors.\n\nA probing classifier generally has no analogous “cold lexical hallucination” phase. It is not about how the model guesses the meaning of an unknown word behaviorally; it is about what can be extracted from internal states.\n\n---\n\n### What each method treats as evidence\n\nA probing classifier treats decodability as evidence:\n\n> If a classifier can recover part-of-speech, syntax, dependency distance, semantic role, etc. from hidden states, then that information is in some sense represented there.\n\nA coinage probe treats lexical uptake and contrast as evidence:\n\n> If a model can move from confabulating about an unknown coined term to reliably distinguishing it from near-neighbors after a minimal definition, then that gap reveals something about how the model’s cognitive substrate supports lexical binding, semantic placement, and contextual concept formation.\n\n---\n\n### Important caveat\n\nThey are not mutually exclusive. One could imagine combining them:\n\n1. introduce a coined term,\n2. collect model hidden states before and after definition,\n3. train or apply probes to see how the representation changes.\n\nBut the canonical **coinage probe** is primarily a behavioral/in-context methodology, while the classic **probing classifier** paradigm is a supervised representational analysis method.",
