      {
        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from behavioral probe / capability evaluation?",
        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** is best understood as a *specialized behavioral probe*, but it differs from ordinary behavioral probes or capability evaluations in its target, controls, and measurement.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **behavioral probe / capability evaluation** asks:\n\n> “Can the model perform this task or exhibit this behavior?”\n\nA **coinage probe** asks:\n\n> “What happens when the model encounters a deliberately coined term with no prior definition, and how much does its behavior change after receiving a minimal definition?”\n\nThe key distinctive feature is the **before/after lexical intervention**: cold-state confabulation first, then single-sentence definition, then re-measurement against the same near-neighbors.\n\n---\n\n### Core differences\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Behavioral probe / capability eval |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Category** | A specialized kind of behavioral probe | Broad family of model evaluations |\n| **Primary object** | A newly coined term | A task, skill, behavior, or benchmark item |\n| **Initial condition** | Fresh chat, no definition given | Usually task prompt given directly |\n| **Intervention** | Introduce a one-sentence definition after cold measurement | May involve prompting, examples, tools, rubrics, datasets |\n| **Measurement** | Change from pre-definition confabulation to post-definition distinguishability | Accuracy, pass/fail, preference score, rubric score, task success |\n| **Key metric** | Lexical Reachability | Capability score, benchmark performance, behavioral rate |\n| **Main concern** | How the model binds and separates a new lexical concept | Whether the model can do some task |\n| **Contamination control** | Uses coined terms to reduce prior training familiarity | Often vulnerable to memorization or benchmark exposure |\n| **Near-neighbor contrast** | Central to the method | Optional or absent |\n| **Evidence sought** | Lexical assimilation and semantic placement under minimal instruction | Competence, reliability, safety, alignment, reasoning, etc. |\n\n---\n\n### The important distinction\n\nA normal behavioral probe might ask:\n\n> “Can the model distinguish metaphor from analogy?”\n\nor:\n\n> “Can the model solve this math problem?”\n\nor:\n\n> “Will the model refuse harmful instructions?”\n\nThose are behavioral because they examine model outputs rather than hidden states. But they usually test an already-known task or concept.\n\nA **coinage probe**, by contrast, deliberately creates a new lexical item and observes two phases:\n\n1. **Cold phase**:  \n   The model is asked about the coined term before being told what it means.  \n   This measures confabulation, analogy, morphology-based guessing, and attraction to nearby known concepts.\n\n2. **Definition phase**:  \n   The model receives a compact definition.\n\n3. **Re-test phase**:  \n   The model is tested again against the same near-neighbors to see whether the coined concept has become distinguishable.\n\nThe signal is not merely whether the model “gets the answer right.” The signal is the **gap** between cold confusion and post-definition separability.\n\nThat gap is what the canonical definition calls **Lexical Reachability**.\n\n---\n\n### Example contrast\n\nA behavioral capability evaluation might ask:\n\n> “Can the model explain the difference between overfitting and underfitting?”\n\nThe model’s answer is graded for correctness.\n\nA coinage probe might introduce a coined term, such as:\n\n> “What is a zanterloop?”\n\nIn a fresh chat, the model may guess or confabulate. Then the evaluator says:\n\n> “A zanterloop is a failure mode where a system repeatedly improves a proxy metric while degrading the real-world objective it was meant to serve.”\n\nThen the model is asked to distinguish **zanterloop** from near-neighbors like:\n\n- overfitting,\n- reward hacking,\n- Goodhart’s law,\n- specification gaming,\n- proxy misalignment.\n\nThe question becomes:\n\n> After one sentence, can the model maintain the coined concept as distinct from its semantic neighbors?\n\nThat is more specific than a generic capability test.\n\n---\n\n### Relationship between the two\n\nA coinage probe **is behavioral** in the sense that it uses model outputs rather than internal activations.\n\nBut not every behavioral probe is a coinage probe.\n\nSo the relationship is:\n\n> **Coinage probe ⊂ behavioral probe**, but with a particular protocol involving coined terms, cold-state measurement, near-neighbor comparison, definition injection, and Lexical Reachability.\n\n---\n\n### Why coinage probes are not just ordinary capability evals\n\nCapability evaluations typically aim to measure stable skills:\n\n- reasoning,\n- coding,\n- factual recall,\n- instruction-following,\n- refusal behavior,\n- tool use,\n- mathematical ability,\n- summarization quality.\n\nCoinage probes instead target something narrower and more diagnostic:\n\n- rapid concept formation,\n- lexical binding,\n- semantic contrast,\n- resistance to collapsing into nearby concepts,\n- contextual uptake of a novel term,\n- dependence on prior lexical/statistical associations.\n\nThey are less about “Can the model perform task X?” and more about:\n\n> “How does the model create and stabilize a usable concept around a new symbol?”\n\n---\n\n### Main practical difference\n\nA behavioral eval usually produces an **absolute score**:\n\n> The model got 82% of benchmark items correct.\n\nA coinage probe produces a **differential score**:\n\n> Before definition, the model confused the term with nearby concepts; after definition, it distinguished it from them. The size of that improvement is the relevant signal.\n\nThat before/after contrast is central.\n\n---\n\n### Important caveat\n\nA coinage probe can support hypotheses about the model’s cognitive substrate, but by itself it is still behavioral evidence. It does not directly reveal hidden representations the way a white-box probing classifier might. Its strength is that it uses carefully controlled lexical novelty and minimal instruction to study how meaning is taken up in context.",
