        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from probing classifier (Alain & Bengio 2016, Hewitt & Manning 2019)?",
        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** and a **probing classifier** are both “probes,” but they probe very different things.\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Probing classifier |\n|---|---|---|\n| What is being tested? | A system’s **behavior with novel or made-up words** | What information is **encoded in internal representations** |\n| Main method | Give the model/person a nonce word or newly coined word and see what they do | Freeze a model, extract hidden states, train a classifier/regressor to predict some property |\n| Example | “This is a *wug*. Now there are two ___.” → tests pluralization | Given a hidden vector, predict POS tag, dependency depth, syntactic distance, etc. |\n| Requires training a new model? | Usually no | Yes, the probe itself is trained |\n| Level of analysis | Input-output behavior | Internal representation analysis |\n| Typical question | “Can the model generalize a rule to unseen words?” | “Is syntactic/semantic information linearly or otherwise recoverable from this layer?” |\n\nIn **Alain & Bengio 2016**, a probing classifier is trained on the activations of a neural network to see what information is available at different layers.\n\nIn **Hewitt & Manning 2019**, a structural probe is trained to determine whether syntactic tree structure is recoverable from contextual word representations.\n\nA **coinage probe**, by contrast, is closer to a **behavioral test** or **nonce-word test**. It asks whether a model can correctly handle an invented word such as *wug*, *dax*, or *blicket*. For example:\n\n> “A dax is a small animal. Two of them are called two ___.”\n\nIf the model answers **daxes**, the test suggests it can apply an English pluralization pattern to a novel lexical item.\n\nSo the core difference is:\n\n> A **coinage probe** probes generalization to novel words through task behavior, whereas a **probing classifier** probes internal representations by training an auxiliary model to decode some property from them.\n\nThey can be combined, though. For example, one could introduce a nonce word into prompts, collect the model’s hidden states for that word, and then train a probing classifier to test whether the model’s internal representation encodes its inferred number, syntactic role, semantic category, or other features.",
