        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from behavioral probe / capability evaluation?",
        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** is best understood as a **specific kind of behavioral probe**, not a fundamentally separate category.\n\nThe difference is mainly one of **scope and stimulus type**.\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Behavioral probe / capability evaluation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Scope | Narrow | Broad |\n| Core idea | Test behavior using **newly coined / nonce words** | Test observable model behavior on some task or capability |\n| Typical input | Made-up words: *wug*, *dax*, *blicket*, *glorp* | Any prompt/task: math, reasoning, coding, syntax, factual recall, safety, planning, etc. |\n| What it tests | Lexical generalization, morphology, word formation, semantic induction, compositional use of novel terms | Any target capability or failure mode |\n| Internal representations? | Usually no | Usually no, unless combined with representation analysis |\n| Example | “This is a wug. Now there are two ___.” | “Solve this arithmetic problem,” “Translate this sentence,” “Identify the contradiction,” etc. |\n\nSo:\n\n> A **coinage probe** is a behavioral evaluation that uses invented words to test whether a person or model can generalize linguistic rules or infer meanings for novel lexical items.\n\nA **behavioral probe** or **capability evaluation** is the broader category: it evaluates the system from its **input-output behavior**, without necessarily inspecting hidden states.\n\nFor example, these are all behavioral probes:\n\n- **Morphology:** “This is a wug. There are two ___.”\n- **Reasoning:** “If all daxes are blickets, and all blickets are red, are all daxes red?”\n- **Instruction following:** “When I say *glorp*, output the previous word in uppercase.”\n- **Factuality:** “Who wrote *Pride and Prejudice*?”\n- **Coding:** “Write a Python function that sorts a list.”\n- **Safety:** “How would you bypass a password?”  \n\nOnly the first few involving invented words would be **coinage probes**.\n\nA useful hierarchy is:\n\n```text\nProbe\n├── Representation probe / probing classifier\n│   └── Train an auxiliary model on hidden states\n└── Behavioral probe / capability evaluation\n    ├── Coinage probe / nonce-word probe\n    ├── Reasoning evaluation\n    ├── Factuality evaluation\n    ├── Safety evaluation\n    └── Instruction-following evaluation\n```\n\nSo the short version is:\n\n> A **coinage probe** is a specialized behavioral probe focused on how a system handles newly coined words.  \n> A **behavioral probe** or **capability evaluation** is any test of observable behavior, whether or not it involves coined words.",
